<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Chartered Institution of Highways &amp; Transportation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (LPG 64)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT is a membership organisation representing over 12,000 people who work in the highways and transportation sector.  CIHT members plan, design, build, operate and maintain best-in-class transport systems and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence to the Committee’s call for evidence on Local Government Procurement. CIHT responses are based on inputs from members of our Procurement &amp; Delivery panel which has experience from across the local government H&amp;T sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? To what extent are local authorities achieving the involvement of local residents in delivering value for money? To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There can be a disconnect between the procuring authority and industry. This can arise in several ways;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The lack of understanding of private sector drivers tends to result in some poor procurements. This has to some extent being repaired by organisations such as CECA and HTMA who help clients understand industry. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Too many procurements do not embrace the wider aspirations of the authorities corporate plans, e.g. training aspirations for apprenticeships etc are not always written into contracts.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Private sector understanding of wider drivers for the public sector often comes directly from contract documentation which may not contain linkages to wider policies or expect the private sector to carry out significant research into wider policies. This is then not reflected in the particular service area where the procurement is being carried out.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Procurement specialist are often blinded to opportunities with existing suppliers and send everything out to tender (as they cannot be criticised for this method of procurement).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Linkages between purpose of highway services and the overall benefit of service is not clearly understood, therefore the focus is too often on reducing overall cost of services without recognising the actual value of the service. The relationship between cost and quality in evaluation of bids is often heavily skewed towards cost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The relationship between length of contracts and overall value for money does not correspond to the political and officer cycle in local authorities – changing priorities are not reflected well in contractual arrangements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There have been successful longer term relationships and more effort needs to be made in understanding those successes and the factors behind them. These factors include;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Long term funding certainty underpinning long term certainty of service delivery on both public and private sector sides</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Appropriate service specification in terms of outputs and outcomes required</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clear and understood risk allocation between the parties</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">selection of partners through appropriate procurement and evaluation criteria</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Contract forms need to reflect appropriate change mechanisms</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q2. Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an attitude in most authorities that says we are special and therefore joint procurement's are not ideal for us. However, many authorities are taking some if not all of the standard methodologies developed by Highways Maintenance Efficiency programme </span><a href="http://www.dft.gov.uk/hmep/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">(HMEP)</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a sector led, DfT sponsored programme and others. This is a positive trend and should be encouraged by all.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PFI methodologies are the most efficient in the transport industry and lessons should be learned from these contracts. The downside is loss of control as the contract runs to a specification developed pre contract.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The good lessons from PFI have not been captured and lessons from ongoing projects are not being successfully monitored. The factors identified in the response to Q1 are reflected in the development of PFI contracts. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst there are wider questions about the overall benefits of PFI in VFM, as a form of funding the highways sector is one where PFI has delivered successful improvements to service delivery in local government particularly in the street lighting and highways maintenance sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q3. How can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives? More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Too many highways individuals involved in procurement in Local Authorities only do this task infrequently and therefore lack knowledge that is normally developed over time. Many of the most knowledgeable Individuals in Procurement are in the private sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities should consider hiring these individuals to develop their procurements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a plethora of “efficiency” initiatives from different sources in the construction sector that are creating significant wastage in the private sector responding to a large number of different frameworks created by different “efficiency” bodies, with no guarantee of any work coming out of them.  The number of authorities and regional bodies with different drivers around efficiency often mask the key purposes of services to meet customer needs with “efficiency” becoming the driver rather than a given in the delivery of public services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An overall approach such as the HMEP programme identified above is a more appropriate way of achieving efficiencies in the highways sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q4. To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most authorities don't understand the needs of their suppliers and market places. The more informed have recently been listening to organisations like HTMA and CECA to get a better appreciation before drafting their contract documents. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities do not appear to appreciate the costs of their tendering methodologies on the private sector, and the fact this all has to recovered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The highways sector is one of the better sectors in local government and the HMEP initiative is adding wider value to the sector. Ultimately there are too many clients in the sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even when flexibility is written into contracts many authorities are reluctant to exercise the clauses as there is often little trust in the private sector - they believe they will lose out. The private sector in highways is generally very collaborative and looking for win win position.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q5. How is regularity and propriety of procurement secured and are the arrangements for detecting and addressing impropriety and fraud effective?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most Authorities are very good at ensuring regularity and propriety but as a result don't always get best value for money as they revert to safest positions at all times (e.g. Tender everything) rather than look for real VFM with current providers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q6. Is local authority procurement fully transparent, audited effectively and does it provide appropriate mechanisms for redress? Specifically, are the arrangements for securing the accountability of procured services and goods to local authorities and local residents adequate and effective? More specifically, to what extent are local authorities able to provide assurance to central government that value for money (in the broadest sense of the term) is delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a membership organisation we are not able to comment sufficiently on this question.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>